---
import ChapterShell from "../../../components/ChapterShell.astro";
import { localePath } from "../../../lib/i18n";
import Section from "../../../components/Section.astro";
import DiagramFigure from "../../../components/diagrams/DiagramFigure.astro";
import DurableTaskKeystone from "../../../components/diagrams/DurableTaskKeystone.astro";
import AttemptContinueFlow from "../../../components/diagrams/AttemptContinueFlow.astro";
import DurableBoundaryFlow from "../../../components/diagrams/DurableBoundaryFlow.astro";
import BudgetLayersFlow from "../../../components/diagrams/BudgetLayersFlow.astro";
import BudgetProjectionRecordingFlow from "../../../components/diagrams/BudgetProjectionRecordingFlow.astro";
import ColdStartResumeFlow from "../../../components/diagrams/ColdStartResumeFlow.astro";
import ParkGrantResumeFlow from "../../../components/diagrams/ParkGrantResumeFlow.astro";
import DurableCheckpointFlow from "../../../components/diagrams/DurableCheckpointFlow.astro";
import TaskLedgerVsTaskRun from "../../../components/diagrams/TaskLedgerVsTaskRun.astro";
---

<ChapterShell chapterId="04" locale="en">
  <div slot="thesis">
    <p>
      When work outlives a Turn, a Run, or even a process, the system must keep a stable identity,
      progress, budgets, and interrupt boundaries. Headless introduces <code>TaskRun</code>: each Agent
      execution becomes a bounded Attempt; cross-Attempt facts append to a Task Event Log and project
      into the next-work view — without rewriting the §01–§03 Runtime; it wraps execution in a durable
      envelope. Interactive Sessions also have a separate <strong>task ledger</strong> (short-key todos)
      — never collapse it with TaskRun. Key line:
      <strong>A task is longer than a turn; durability begins by giving the task its own log.</strong>
    </p>
  </div>

  <Section
    id="scene"
    label="§04 · Scene"
    title="Start from a task that cannot finish in one round"
    lede="Session chat alone cannot answer Attempt, budget, park, or workspace ownership."
  >
    <p>
      Suppose the task is: read a large codebase, migrate an old API, fix the build step by step, and
      pause at high-risk permissions for confirmation. It may: do inventory only on the first round; end
      a Run on a tool-step cap while the task is unfinished; need a second execution that knows which
      files were checked and which todos are open; park waiting for approval; resume hours later;
      survive a process restart that wiped in-memory loop counters and the active backend; and hold its
      workspace in a local temp dir, an external container, or a remote executor.
    </p>
    <p>
      Turn expresses one Q&amp;A; Run expresses one concrete execution; the RuntimeEvent ledger can
      replay model and tool experience — the fact layer already locked in §01–§03. A long task still
      must answer another set of questions:
    </p>
    <pre class="code-block" aria-label="Long-task control questions">What is the stable ID of this long-lived goal?
How many attempts have already run?
How much budget remains?
Which progress snapshots are still valid?
Is the task running, waiting for approval, or stopped by budget?
What context should the next execution inherit?
Is the workspace still the one left by the previous Attempt?
Who may take over the next step?</pre>
    <blockquote class="pull">
      Headless’s real problem is how to turn an open goal across Attempts, parks, and even process
      restarts into a projectable Task Event history — not how to pretend one Invocation can live
      forever.
    </blockquote>
  </Section>

  <Section
    id="keystone"
    label="§04 · Keystone"
    title="TaskRun is a durable envelope outside the Runtime"
    lede="Headless does not reimplement the Agent Runtime; it organizes Runtime execution into a long task lifecycle."
  >
    <DiagramFigure
      prototype
      caption="Fig. 1 · TaskRun wraps bounded Attempts; cross-Attempt facts enter the Task Event Log and project into a next-work view."
      alt="TaskRun shell with Attempt 1/2, Task Event Log to dashed TaskRun Projection; invariant: a task is longer than a turn."
    >
      <DurableTaskKeystone />
    </DiagramFigure>

    <p>Execution identity has four layers with different lifecycles — do not collapse them:</p>
    <ul class="plain-list">
      <li><strong>TaskRun</strong> — who the long-lived goal is from start to terminal (across Attempts)</li>
      <li><strong>Attempt</strong> — one budget-bounded progress slice (one task-level try)</li>
      <li><strong>Turn</strong> — one input/reply exchange handed to the Agent</li>
      <li><strong>Run / Invocation</strong> — one model-and-tool loop start to finish</li>
    </ul>
    <pre class="code-block" aria-label="Task projection and progress">TaskRunProjection(t) = Project(TaskEvents[0..t])

Long task progress
  = sequence of bounded Attempts
  + durable Task Events between them
  + explicitly selected continuation state

≠ one immortal Invocation</pre>
    <p>
      Projection is not a second mutable Task truth. CLI inspect, resume planning, prompt replay, and
      export should all derive from Task Events — the same discipline as §01 (“state is a function of
      the log”) and §03 (“checkpoint is a projection”), with a long-task control plane as the consumer.
      The figure intentionally omits workspace: workspace lifecycle is not always as durable as TaskRun.
    </p>
    <p>
      After a headless finish, <code>TaskRunProjection.executionLineage</code> (and per-Attempt lineage)
      is replayed from Task Events such as <code>task_attempt_execution_linked</code>: it points at
      Session / Invocation / AgentRun and inclusive Runtime coverage without copying Runtime facts into
      the Task ledger. Inspector and cursor contract:
      <a href={localePath("en", "chapters/01-log-is-the-runtime") + "#execution-evidence"}
        >§01 · #execution-evidence</a
      >.
    </p>
  </Section>

  <Section
    id="session"
    label="§04 · Identity"
    title="Why Session is still not TaskRun"
    lede="Conversation ownership and durable orchestration must not contaminate each other."
  >
    <p>
      A Session can span Turns and keep model history, but it mainly answers “who owns these
      dialogues.” A TaskRun must also express: Attempt count and outcomes, loop-budget usage, pause for
      permission/budget/intervention, cross-Attempt progress/evidence, workspace-lease ownership,
      continue / retry / stop / abort, and the active task policy. Ordinary interactive chat should not
      be forced to carry those control fields; different Attempts may currently create different
      Sessions / AgentRuns.
    </p>
    <p>
      Reference direction: Task Events store <code>sessionId</code> / <code>agentRunId</code>; the Session
      header is not TaskRun truth. Stuffing task-control fields into Session forces unattended semantics
      onto interactive chat; using Session headers as Task truth makes park / budget / multi-Attempt
      dishonest after restart.
    </p>
    <aside class="history-aside">
      <p class="history-aside__tag">History aside</p>
      <p>
        Headless TaskRun orchestration:
        <a href={localePath("en", "history/pr/567")}>maka:pr:567</a>. Architecture chapter
        land:
        <a href={localePath("en", "history/pr/773")}>maka:pr:773</a>
        (docs: durable task loop chapter). Interactive session task ledger is the next section —
        <a href="#ledger">#ledger</a> — do not conflate the two.
      </p>
    </aside>
  </Section>

  <Section
    id="ledger"
    label="§04 · Session ledger"
    title="Session task ledger ≠ TaskRun"
    lede="Interactive short-key todos are advisory control state; Headless TaskRun is the cross-Attempt durable envelope."
  >
    <DiagramFigure
      caption="Fig. 1b · Two “task” objects: Session ledger (id+key, four tools, advisory status) vs TaskRun (Attempts, budget, park/grant)."
      alt="Side-by-side contrast of Session task ledger and Headless TaskRun."
    >
      <TaskLedgerVsTaskRun />
    </DiagramFigure>

    <div class="table-wrap" role="region" aria-label="Ledger vs TaskRun contrast" tabindex="0">
      <table class="proto-table">
        <thead>
          <tr>
            <th scope="col">Axis</th>
            <th scope="col">Session task ledger</th>
            <th scope="col">Headless TaskRun</th>
          </tr>
        </thead>
        <tbody>
          <tr>
            <th scope="row">Scope</th>
            <td>Work items inside an interactive Session</td>
            <td>Benchmark / automation execution envelope</td>
          </tr>
          <tr>
            <th scope="row">Identity</th>
            <td>Durable UUID <code>id</code> + short <code>key</code> (<code>T1</code> / <code>T1.1</code>)</td>
            <td><code>taskRunId</code> + Attempt ids</td>
          </tr>
          <tr>
            <th scope="row">Storage</th>
            <td><code>task-events.jsonl</code> + <code>tasks.json</code> projection</td>
            <td>Per-TaskRun Task Event Log JSONL</td>
          </tr>
          <tr>
            <th scope="row">Status meaning</th>
            <td>Advisory (<code>pending</code>…<code>cancelled</code>)</td>
            <td>Orchestration lifecycle (queued/started/parked/terminal)</td>
          </tr>
          <tr>
            <th scope="row">Model surface</th>
            <td>Turn-tail injection + four <code>task_*</code> tools</td>
            <td>Headless continue / budget loop — not a chat todo list</td>
          </tr>
          <tr>
            <th scope="row">Evidence authority</th>
            <td>Compact reason/evidence; <strong>never</strong> overrides FS/git/test/tool truth</td>
            <td>Progress/evidence for loop decisions; still references RuntimeEvents</td>
          </tr>
        </tbody>
      </table>
    </div>

    <h3 class="subhead">Identity and hierarchy</h3>
    <p>
      Reads/updates accept UUID or short key. Keys allocate inside a per-session serialized write
      queue; a child stores the parent UUID in <code>parentId</code> and extends under the parent key.
      Parent/child edges must deepen by exactly one segment (<code>T1</code> → <code>T1.1</code>);
      skipped levels invalidate the projection and fail closed. No children under terminal parents; a
      parent cannot become <code>completed</code> while any descendant is non-terminal.
    </p>

    <h3 class="subhead">Status, evidence, and resumeTrust</h3>
    <pre class="code-block" aria-label="Ledger status transitions">pending → in_progress | cancelled
in_progress → blocked | completed | failed | cancelled
blocked → in_progress | cancelled | failed
failed → pending | cancelled
completed → in_progress   only explicitReopen
cancelled → pending       only explicitReopen</pre>
    <p>
      Entering blocked / failed / completed requires <code>blockedReason</code> /
      <code>failureReason</code> / <code>completionEvidence</code>. <code>resumeTrust</code> (trusted /
      needs_revalidation / stale / repaired / untrusted) is a system diagnostic: model-visible turn-tail
      and <code>task_list</code> / <code>task_get</code> <strong>do not inject</strong> it; debug/export
      may.
    </p>

    <h3 class="subhead">Tools and child agents</h3>
    <p>
      <code>task_create</code> / <code>task_update</code> / <code>task_list</code> /
      <code>task_get</code> only mutate/read local session state — they do not dispatch work.
      <code>MAKA_TASK_LEDGER_TOOLS=false</code> disables registration.
      <code>agent_spawn(task_id=…)</code> claims the task after the child turn is allocated
      (<code>in_progress</code> + child_agent owner); a successful child <strong>does not</strong>
      auto-complete the parent — the parent must verify and supply <code>completionEvidence</code>. An
      active task cannot be stolen by another child turn.
    </p>

    <p>
      Prompt-tail budget is ~8 000 characters, prioritizing in_progress / pending / blocked branches;
      terminal tasks logically archive after seven days (storage stays append-only). An external Goal
      evaluator still decides first; a one-shot reminder fires only when the Goal continues with
      actionable keys — the ledger is neither Goal truth nor a §05 verifier.
    </p>

    <aside class="history-aside">
      <p class="history-aside__tag">Verification</p>
      <p>
        Authority: <code>docs/session-task-ledger-lifecycle.md</code> ·
        <code>packages/core/src/task-ledger.ts</code> ·
        <code>task-ledger-store.ts</code> · <code>task-ledger-tools.ts</code> and matching
        <code>__tests__</code>. Outline:
        <code>docs/research/session-task-ledger-deep-outline.md</code>.
      </p>
    </aside>
  </Section>

  <Section
    id="events"
    label="§04 · Task Events"
    title="The Task Event Log is the long-task control-plane source of truth"
    lede="Append-only JSONL; project from the head — never write truth back from a mutable table."
  >
    <p>
      <code>TaskRunStore</code> persists <code>TaskEvent</code> as append-only JSONL files keyed by
      <code>taskRunId</code>; in-process appends for one TaskRun are serialized via a promise queue.
      <code>projectTaskRun()</code> replays from the head to compute status, Attempts, latest progress,
      evidence, permission facts, parked state, warnings, and refs into Runtime execution.
    </p>
    <p>Control-plane event families a reader should be able to name:</p>
    <ul class="plain-list">
      <li>TaskRun created / queued / started / terminal</li>
      <li>Attempt started / completed</li>
      <li>autonomous decision and runtime feedback</li>
      <li>heavy-task: mode, inventory, todos, self-check, workspace observation, compact evidence</li>
      <li>isolation policy, workspace lease, tool-executor identity</li>
      <li>permission request / grant / decision; inbox item / resolution / <code>needs_approval</code></li>
    </ul>
    <p>
      Runtime Events hold semantic facts of each Agent execution; Task Events hold cross-execution task
      facts. Task Events <strong>reference</strong> Runtime execution — they do not copy or rewrite
      RuntimeEvent truth.
    </p>
    <aside class="history-aside">
      <p class="history-aside__tag">Archive delta · heavy-task three planes</p>
      <p>
        Archive <code>heavy-task-mainline-system-design.md</code> locks that end-to-end is not “string
        the functions”: a <strong>control plane</strong> (autonomous loop / retry / timeout), a
        <strong>model-visible plane</strong> (prompt policy / inventory / todo / self-check tools), and
        a <strong>ledger-projection plane</strong> (TaskRun events → projection / export) run together.
        The planes are not interchangeable — self-check pass ≠ control terminal ≠ official verifier;
        compact evidence ≠ raw public execution; retry = projection continuation, not checkpoint
        resume. Live state is not a separate memory store — it is a projection over typed Task Events.
        Current authority is this chapter / §05 gates and headless code; absorb record:
        <code>docs/research/archive-mine-delta-absorb-batch2-2026-07-21.md</code>.
      </p>
    </aside>
  </Section>

  <Section
    id="durable"
    label="§04 · Current"
    title="What is actually durable"
    lede="Durable control-plane facts ≠ the whole execution world is checkpointed."
  >
    <DiagramFigure
      caption="Fig. 2 · The TaskRun ledger owns control-plane facts; workspace / live stream / auto-takeover remain Target gaps."
      alt="Left column: Current ledger owns. Right column: Not guaranteed by ledger alone."
    >
      <DurableBoundaryFlow />
    </DiagramFigure>
    <p><strong>Clearly durable today:</strong></p>
    <ul class="plain-list">
      <li>TaskRun identity and appended Task Events</li>
      <li>Attempt / progress / decision / permission / lifecycle facts recorded in those events</li>
      <li>Refs to Session, AgentRun, RuntimeEvents, and artifacts</li>
    </ul>
    <p><strong>Not guaranteed by the TaskRun ledger alone:</strong></p>
    <ul class="plain-list">
      <li>Current bytes of a throwaway workspace</li>
      <li>Live provider streams / tool-process handles</li>
      <li>In-memory backend, abort controller, loop closure</li>
      <li>Whether an external executor still holds the same workspace</li>
      <li>Whether a scheduler auto-claims after process restart</li>
    </ul>
    <div class="stub">
      <p class="stub__tag">Precision bar</p>
      <p>
        Today there is durable, replayable Task control state — <strong>not</strong> a complete
        crash-resumable task executor. Teaching must label that gap; ledger replay must not be sold as
        live-world takeover.
      </p>
    </div>
  </Section>

  <Section
    id="attempt"
    label="§04 · Attempt"
    title="How one Attempt reuses the Runtime spine"
    lede="An Attempt is a progress slice, not a synonym for failure; continue means a new Attempt."
  >
    <DiagramFigure
      caption="Fig. 3 · Attempt ends → append TaskEvent → policy gate → project next-work; continue = new Attempt."
      alt="Five steps: runTaskOnce, Attempt ends, Append TaskEvt, Policy gate, Next view."
    >
      <AttemptContinueFlow />
    </DiagramFigure>
    <p>
      <code>TaskAgentController.runTaskOnce()</code> wraps one Attempt around the Runtime. Teaching
      compression of the sequence:
    </p>
    <ol class="plain-list numbered">
      <li>Validate backend isolation and task setup; resolve TaskRun/Attempt identity and intervention policy</li>
      <li>Read Heavy-task progress / self-check / compact evidence from the existing projection into this instruction</li>
      <li>Append mode, isolation, and prior permission-grant facts; prepare workspace; record lease and executor identity</li>
      <li>Create Session and <code>AgentRun</code>; append <code>task_run_started</code> / <code>task_attempt_started</code></li>
      <li>Run <code>AgentRun → AiSdkFlow → RuntimeRunner</code>; fold Invocation refs / budget / tool activity into Task-level feedback</li>
      <li>Handle permission intervention or bounded Heavy-task repair; append next Attempt / TaskRun state</li>
    </ol>
    <p>
      This path bypasses the <code>SessionManager.sendMessage()</code> facade and assembles Runtime core
      components directly — it needs a non-streaming <code>InvocationResult</code>, its own Task Event
      Log, isolated backend lifecycle, and Attempt post-processing, not a second model loop.
    </p>
    <p>
      An Attempt may end on normal stop, execution failure, incomplete information, permission block,
      budget exhaustion, cancel, or abort. Outer policy chooses <code>continue</code> / <code>retry</code> /
      <code>stop</code> / <code>abort</code>. <code>AutonomousAgentLoop</code> creates a new Attempt on
      every <code>runTaskOnce()</code> — it does not resume an old RuntimeRunner instruction pointer or
      resurrect an exited tool process.
    </p>
  </Section>

  <Section
    id="budget"
    label="§04 · Budget"
    title="Three budget layers give the loop a provable boundary"
    lede="“Continue until done” is not a safe terminal condition; hard caps dominate custom policy."
  >
    <DiagramFigure
      caption="Fig. 4 · AutonomousLoopBudget: maxAttempts · maxRuntimeSteps (summed across Attempts) · maxWallTimeMs; enforceCaps reapplies."
      alt="Three columns: maxAttempts, cumulative maxRuntimeSteps, maxWallTimeMs."
    >
      <BudgetLayersFlow />
    </DiagramFigure>
    <ul class="plain-list">
      <li><code>maxAttempts</code> — how many Attempts a TaskRun may start (checked before/after Attempt)</li>
      <li><code>maxRuntimeSteps</code> — Runtime steps <strong>summed across all Attempts</strong> (checked after Attempt)</li>
      <li><code>maxWallTimeMs</code> — total wall time of the TaskRun loop (checked before/after Attempt)</li>
    </ul>
    <p>
      <code>LoopBudgetSnapshot</code> hands used and max to decision policy. Even if custom policy asks
      continue/retry, <code>enforceCaps()</code> reapplies hard limits — and if the Attempt already
      <code>passed</code>, forces <code>stop</code> (authoritative verification beats “try again”).
    </p>
    <DiagramFigure
      caption="Fig. 4b · Live loop counters · enforceCaps · snapshots written into Task Events — auditable ≠ cold-start resumable."
      alt="Three columns: in-memory startedAt/counters, enforceCaps, autonomous_decision_recorded."
    >
      <BudgetProjectionRecordingFlow />
    </DiagramFigure>
    <div class="table-wrap" role="region" aria-label="Budget: live vs projected" tabindex="0">
      <table class="proto-table">
        <thead>
          <tr>
            <th scope="col">Fact</th>
            <th scope="col">Where it lands</th>
            <th scope="col">Cold-start honest?</th>
          </tr>
        </thead>
        <tbody>
          <tr>
            <th scope="row">Attempt count</th>
            <td>Task Events + snapshot.<code>attemptsUsed</code></td>
            <td>Rebuildable</td>
          </tr>
          <tr>
            <th scope="row">Runtime steps summed</th>
            <td>Live sum of <code>resultRecord.steps</code>; also in snapshot</td>
            <td>History auditable; live accumulator needs care</td>
          </tr>
          <tr>
            <th scope="row">Wall elapsed</th>
            <td><code>now - startedAt</code> (in-process)</td>
            <td><strong>No</strong> — <code>startedAt</code> is not durable</td>
          </tr>
          <tr>
            <th scope="row">Decision + reason</th>
            <td><code>autonomous_decision_recorded</code> (embeds full snapshot)</td>
            <td>Auditable</td>
          </tr>
          <tr>
            <th scope="row">Budget terminal</th>
            <td>
              <code>task_run_budget_exhausted</code>; may first open a
              <code>needs_approval</code> inbox when intervention allows extension
            </td>
            <td>Auditable</td>
          </tr>
        </tbody>
      </table>
    </div>
    <p>
      So budget use is <strong>auditable</strong> (each decision pins a snapshot into the Task Event
      Log), but a generic projection still cannot unambiguously restore every loop counter at an
      arbitrary restart (Target: durable budget accounting). See
      <code>docs/research/autonomous-budget-projection-deep-outline.md</code>.
    </p>
  </Section>

  <Section
    id="progress"
    label="§04 · Progress"
    title="Bounded progress projection across Attempts"
    lede="Do not shove the previous Attempt’s natural-language reply back into the prompt."
  >
    <p>Heavy-task mode introduces structured, append-only progress facts:</p>
    <ul class="plain-list">
      <li>
        <strong>Inventory</strong> (<code>inventory_submit</code>) — full snapshot (files/artifacts, status,
        purpose, open questions); latest replaces current inventory in the projection; older snapshots stay
        in the log.
      </li>
      <li>
        <strong>Todos</strong> (<code>todo_update</code>) — full todo snapshot (ID, priority, status,
        content, optional kind); projection can stably find the active todo.
      </li>
      <li>
        <strong>Compact Evidence</strong> — bounded public evidence around Bash/Read/Grep/Write/Edit/Glob
        (summaries, truncation refs, source links, mutation metadata); large stdout / full bodies / raw
        diffs do not flood the task prompt.
      </li>
      <li>
        <strong>Self-check</strong> — public reason, command/artifact evidence, and hygiene (see §05);
        advisory with bounded repair — not hidden authority.
      </li>
    </ul>
    <pre class="code-block" aria-label="Progress projection chain">Full task history remains in Task Events
  → latest progress snapshots are selected
  → recent public evidence is bounded
  → next Attempt receives a continuation-oriented prompt view</pre>
    <p>
      On the next Attempt,
      <code>renderHeavyTaskProgressForPrompt()</code> /
      <code>renderHeavyTaskSelfCheckForPrompt()</code> /
      <code>renderHeavyTaskEvidenceForPrompt()</code> render bounded text from the projection. This is
      not full replay, and it does not claim omitted raw output is still in the prompt.
    </p>
  </Section>

  <Section
    id="continue"
    label="§04 · Continuation"
    title="“Continue” has at least three paths — do not merge them into one resume"
    lede="Harbor Cell Turn · Autonomous Attempt · parked CLI resume — different semantics; events must be explicit."
  >
    <DiagramFigure
      caption="Fig. 5 · Three continuations: same-Session Harbor Turn · autonomous new Attempt · parked needs_approval; unified resume remains Target."
      alt="Columns: Autonomous continue, Parked resume, Cold start reload, Target unified resume gap."
    >
      <ColdStartResumeFlow />
    </DiagramFigure>

    <h3 class="subhead">1. New Turn inside the same Harbor Cell</h3>
    <p>
      Loops <code>SessionManager.sendMessage()</code> inside the same Session and container workspace.
      Today it continues only when the previous Invocation ended on a tool-step cap or incomplete tool
      calls. The next Turn uses a fixed continuation prompt under <code>maxTurns</code> and
      <code>maxTotalRuntimeSteps</code> (defaults when enabled: at most 3 Turns; total Runtime steps
      default to 50 per Turn). Closest path to “keep working on the same workspace,” still multiple new
      Invocations — not instruction-level resume.
    </p>

    <h3 class="subhead">2. New Attempt from the Autonomous Loop</h3>
    <p>
      continue/retry calls <code>runTaskOnce()</code> again. Heavy-task state projects from Task Events
      into the new instruction; when <code>replayPriorAttemptRuntimeContext</code> is on, prior Attempt
      RuntimeEvents are also folded into the next Runtime context — that switch is not mandatory
      semantics by default. When off, cross-Attempt continuation mainly rides instruction feedback and
      TaskRun progress projection.
    </p>

    <h3 class="subhead">3. CLI resume of a parked permission</h3>
    <DiagramFigure
      caption="Fig. 6 · park → Inbox / needs_approval → resolve + grant facts → new Attempt; forbid rewriting an old tool call after the fact."
      alt="Four-step protocol: Permission park, Inbox item, CLI resume writes grant, forbid post-hoc auth."
    >
      <ParkGrantResumeFlow />
    </DiagramFigure>
    <p>
      When intervention policy is <code>park</code>, a permission request becomes a
      <code>TaskPermissionRequest</code>, Inbox item, Attempt <code>needs_approval</code>, and TaskRun
      parked state. Today’s <code>task resume</code> mainly serves this path: resolve the inbox, open a
      new Attempt, and append grant facts to the Task Event Log. A late grant
      <strong>must not</strong> post-hoc authorize a tool call that already handed off — Resume is new
      input for the next Attempt, not resurrection of the old call stack.
    </p>

    <h3 class="subhead">Cold-start ledger reload</h3>
    <p>
      After process restart, reload JSONL and <code>projectTaskRun()</code>. What returns is control-plane
      truth; teaching must not treat attempts/steps as “reset because the process is new” — yet full
      loop-counter recovery is still Target (see checkpoint below). Without workspace / executor
      ownership evidence, do not claim safe live-world takeover.
    </p>
  </Section>

  <Section
    id="workspace"
    label="§04 · Workspace"
    title="A lease records ownership — it is not a workspace checkpoint"
    lede="Current TaskRun durability preserves control history; workspace continuity remains carrier-dependent."
  >
    <p>
      Default local <code>runTaskOnce()</code> creates a throwaway copy of the task fixture per Attempt and
      cleans it in <code>finally</code> (fixture symlinks are rejected to avoid host escape after copy).
      Task Events record <code>WorkspaceLeaseFacts</code> (lease ID, TaskRun/Attempt identity, source and
      actual path, writable, cleanup policy, createdAt, …), but <strong>recording a lease ≠ saving
      workspace bytes</strong>. The next Attempt recopies the fixture by default; mutations from the prior
      Attempt do not appear just because the TaskRun ID matches.
    </p>
    <p>
      External isolation may provide a stable <code>workspaceDir</code>, and a Harbor Cell can share one
      workspace while the container lives, but TaskRunStore does not own that external workspace’s
      snapshot, lease renewal, or fencing protocol. A throwaway directory isolates fixture mutation — it
      is not an OS security sandbox; real model-backed backends must supply
      <code>RealBackendIsolation</code>. Headless validates isolation-record shape and non-empty labels —
      filesystem / network / process / secret isolation is fulfilled by the external executor. See
      <a href="#harbor-trust">#harbor-trust</a>.
    </p>
  </Section>

  <Section
    id="harbor-trust"
    label="§04 · Harbor trust"
    title="Eval distrusts by default: isolation is an assertion, not a guess"
    lede="The measured config may be adversarial; without a boundary, fail closed. Harbor is an executor carrier — not a second Task truth."
  >
    <p>
      <code>@maka/headless</code> eval posture is hard: the config under test is
      <strong>untrusted by construction</strong> and must not reach host credentials. Without OS-level
      isolation, the only safe enforcement is fail closed by default — the CLI still wires only the
      inert <code>fake</code> backend; a model-backed backend in a JSON spec exits non-zero unless the
      programmatic API supplies an explicit isolation record.
    </p>
    <h3 class="subhead">RealBackendIsolation</h3>
    <p>
      Real-model eval must pass <code>realBackendIsolation</code> (Current:
      <code>kind: 'external'</code>) plus <code>registerBackends</code>. The record is an
      <strong>assertion</strong> that tool execution already sits outside the host credential process
      (Harbor / Terminal-Bench / Docker workspace executor, …) with a non-empty <code>label</code> —
      an accidental truthy object must not enable a real backend. For the standard tool surface, use
      <code>buildIsolatedHeadlessTools(executor)</code>: Bash plus Read/Write/Edit/Glob/Grep route
      through the boundary; absolute paths, <code>..</code> escapes, and absolute globs are rejected
      before dispatch. Read’s line-number/binary guards and Edit’s matcher stay headless-owned even
      when bytes are read/written on a remote executor.
    </p>
    <h3 class="subhead">Three “sandboxes” that must not merge</h3>
    <ul class="plain-list">
      <li><strong>Throwaway workspace</strong> — per-Attempt fixture copy (section above).</li>
      <li>
        <strong>OS Seatbelt / PermissionProfile</strong> — Desktop Runtime platform transform (see
        <a href={localePath("en", "chapters/01-log-is-the-runtime") + "#sandbox"}>§01 #sandbox</a>);
        orthogonal to Harbor.
      </li>
      <li>
        <strong>Harbor / external container</strong> — agent-visible shell/fs in the task container; A/B
        posture gives containers only a per-cell host proxy capability — never access/refresh tokens or
        key-file paths.
      </li>
    </ul>
    <h3 class="subhead">Harbor modes and failure classes</h3>
    <p>
      Cell mode runs a bounded cell on the container side; task-run host-bridge
      (<code>MAKA_HARBOR_MODE=task-run</code>) runs the full TaskRun controller on the host and bridges
      tool execution into the task container (container installs nothing). Resume semantics remain in
      <a href="#continue">#continue</a> — trust boundary ≠ resume protocol.
    </p>
    <h3 id="harness-ab-ops" class="subhead">Harness A/B ops surface (dig v4)</h3>
    <p>
      Trust protocol remains fake-only + RealBackendIsolation; dig v4 deepens headless README ops: Codex
      A/B profile reasoning effort is now <code>xhigh</code> (not legacy <code>max</code>). Use
      <code>MAKA_HARNESS_AB_TASK_IDS</code> (comma-separated frozen Terminal-Bench 2.1 ids) with an
      explicit <code>MAKA_HARNESS_AB_RUN_ID</code> for a resumable subset. Execution policy is
      independent of the competitor profile —
      <code>MAKA_HARNESS_AB_PAIR_CONCURRENCY</code> (1–4) and
      <code>MAKA_HARNESS_AB_ARM_EXECUTION</code> (<code>sequential|parallel</code>), defaulting safely
      to one pair + sequential arms; the immutable manifest freezes effective values and rejects
      changes on resume. Isolated containers may expose images to model vision — still without host
      credentials.
    </p>
    <p>
      <code>classifyExternalHarborBenchmarkFailure</code> separates infra (should throw / non-zero),
      agent_incomplete (scored data, no throw), and budget_exhausted (no throw). Failed verification is
      valid benchmark data (process may exit 0); invalid specs / crashes before a result are infra.
      Grading requires <code>verification.protectedPaths</code>: restore from the pristine fixture after
      the agent and before the command — rewriting tests must not cheat.
    </p>
    <h3 id="harbor-failure" class="subhead">Failure stories</h3>
    <div class="table-wrap" role="region" aria-label="Harbor failure matrix" tabindex="0">
      <table class="proto-table">
        <thead>
          <tr>
            <th scope="col">Situation</th>
            <th scope="col">Result</th>
          </tr>
        </thead>
        <tbody>
          <tr>
            <td>CLI asks for real backend without isolation</td>
            <td>Non-zero refuse</td>
          </tr>
          <tr>
            <td>Missing / empty isolation label</td>
            <td>Validation fail</td>
          </tr>
          <tr>
            <td>Agent rewrites tests under <code>protectedPaths</code></td>
            <td>Restored from pristine; verify sees clean fixture</td>
          </tr>
          <tr>
            <td>Agent fails verification</td>
            <td>Valid scored data; process may exit 0</td>
          </tr>
          <tr>
            <td>Invalid spec / crash before result</td>
            <td>Infra; non-zero</td>
          </tr>
          <tr>
            <td><code>isolation_required</code> / <code>setup_failed</code></td>
            <td>infra_failure; shouldThrow</td>
          </tr>
          <tr>
            <td>Budget / timeout patterns</td>
            <td>budget_exhausted; shouldThrow false</td>
          </tr>
          <tr>
            <td>Agent incomplete / tool_failed</td>
            <td>agent_incomplete; shouldThrow false</td>
          </tr>
          <tr>
            <td>Path escape in isolated tools</td>
            <td>Reject before exec</td>
          </tr>
        </tbody>
      </table>
    </div>
    <h3 id="terminal-bench-read" class="subhead">How to read the Terminal-Bench writeup (cite-only)</h3>
    <p>
      Specimen <code>docs/eval/terminal-bench-2.1-maka-vs-kimi-code-v11.md</code> is a
      <strong>frozen A/B score snapshot</strong> plus harness-asymmetry notes — <strong>not</strong> a
      second Harbor failure taxonomy. Read it as: (1) absolute scores are throughput-depressed lower
      bounds, not model ceilings; (2) relative gaps are harness asymmetries first (context-budget prune,
      system/tool surface), not “who thinks harder”; (3) WAL
      <code>operator_authorized_*</code> recoveries are orthogonal to
      <code>classifyExternalHarborBenchmarkFailure</code>’s infra / agent_incomplete / budget_exhausted —
      admission audit vs throw/no-throw protocol. This page already teaches the protocol; the writeup
      stays cite-only — Destination does not import the score table.
    </p>
    <aside class="history-aside">
      <p class="history-aside__tag">Verification</p>
      <p>
        <code>packages/headless/README.md</code> · <code>isolation.ts</code> ·
        <code>harbor-failure-policy.ts</code> and <code>__tests__/harbor-*.test.ts</code>. Outline:
        <code>docs/research/headless-harbor-trust-deep-outline.md</code>. Eval writeup:
        <code>docs/eval/terminal-bench-2.1-maka-vs-kimi-code-v11.md</code> (cite-only).
      </p>
    </aside>
  </Section>

  <Section
    id="swarm"
    label="§04 · Swarm / Team"
    title="Bounded fan-out and Expert Teams: child agents are not a second durable loop"
    lede="Swarm is structured-concurrency convenience; Team adds mailbox and claim. Both sit on ordinary child AgentRuns."
  >
    <p>
      <strong>Agent Swarm</strong> (<code>agent_swarm</code>) lets the main Agent submit 1..32
      independent items once; the local worker pool defaults to concurrency 3 (cap 5); the whole input
      validates before any child starts; results project in input order. It is not a workflow runtime:
      no <code>SwarmRun</code>, second event ledger, checkpoint, or background owner. Every started item
      is an ordinary child <code>AgentRun</code>; child toolsets exclude <code>agent_swarm</code> (no
      nested batches). Partial failure keeps successful siblings; parent cancel signals active children,
      prevents queued starts, joins, and returns explicit cancelled rows for never-started items.
    </p>
    <h3 class="subhead">Choosing an execution model</h3>
    <div class="table-wrap" role="region" aria-label="Fan-out model choice" tabindex="0">
      <table class="proto-table">
        <thead>
          <tr>
            <th scope="col">Need</th>
            <th scope="col">Prefer</th>
            <th scope="col">Why</th>
          </tr>
        </thead>
        <tbody>
          <tr>
            <td>Small or tightly coupled work</td>
            <td>Main Agent directly</td>
            <td>Delegation overhead exceeds parallelism</td>
          </tr>
          <tr>
            <td>One specialist result, or next depends on prior</td>
            <td>Sequential <code>agent_spawn</code></td>
            <td>Explicit dependency; refine prompts</td>
          </tr>
          <tr>
            <td>Several finite independent items + one synthesis</td>
            <td><code>agent_swarm</code></td>
            <td>Bounded pool, stable order, isolated failures</td>
          </tr>
          <tr>
            <td>Roles, mailbox, task claiming</td>
            <td>Expert Team</td>
            <td>Lead adjudication + mailbox + Task Ledger claim</td>
          </tr>
          <tr>
            <td>DAG / retries / distributed orchestration</td>
            <td>Rive (not this Runtime default)</td>
            <td>Needs a separate durable orchestration authority</td>
          </tr>
        </tbody>
      </table>
    </div>
    <h3 class="subhead">Three concurrency boundaries</h3>
    <ol class="plain-list numbered">
      <li>Subagent tool admission — how many subagent tool calls one turn may open.</li>
      <li>Local Swarm concurrency — workers inside one batch.</li>
      <li>
        Shared child-run permits — real child executions across <code>agent_spawn</code> /
        <code>expert_dispatch</code> / <code>agent_swarm</code>.
      </li>
    </ol>
    <p>
      UI/CLI/telemetry project only bounded summaries plus child <code>runId</code>/<code>turnId</code>
      refs — never raw child prompts, tool args, or tool output. Child AgentRuns remain lifecycle and
      evidence authority.
    </p>
    <h3 class="subhead">Expert Team</h3>
    <p>
      A lead persona runs in the main session (label <code>mode:expert-team:&lt;teamId&gt;</code>) and
      fans out via <code>expert_dispatch</code>. Members are personas under archetypes (e.g.
      <code>local_read</code>) that may <strong>narrow, never widen</strong> tools. Members get
      <code>team_message</code> / <code>team_inbox</code> / <code>team_task_list</code> /
      <code>team_task_claim</code>; they may atomically claim one eligible Task Ledger item owned by the
      current parent lead AgentRun, but completion and adjudication stay with the lead. Mailboxes scope
      by team + lead run; role addresses are shared (not invocation-private); cursors are caller-owned
      (<code>after_seq</code>). Members never receive <code>expert_dispatch</code> — no nested teams.
    </p>
    <div class="stub">
      <p class="stub__tag">Boundary vs TaskRun</p>
      <p>
        Swarm/Team child AgentRuns solve <strong>foreground fan-out and collaboration</strong>; Headless
        <code>TaskRun</code> solves the cross-Attempt durable envelope. Neither is the session task
        ledger (corpus #49). Do not read one <code>agent_swarm</code> call as a cross-process durable
        checkpoint.
      </p>
    </div>
    <h3 id="swarm-failure" class="subhead">Failure stories</h3>
    <div class="table-wrap" role="region" aria-label="Swarm/Team failure matrix" tabindex="0">
      <table class="proto-table">
        <thead>
          <tr>
            <th scope="col">Situation</th>
            <th scope="col">Result</th>
          </tr>
        </thead>
        <tbody>
          <tr>
            <td>Nested <code>agent_swarm</code> in child</td>
            <td>Tool excluded / unavailable</td>
          </tr>
          <tr>
            <td>Invalid item before start</td>
            <td>Whole call fails; no partial start</td>
          </tr>
          <tr>
            <td>One child fails</td>
            <td>Siblings kept; aggregate status reflects mix</td>
          </tr>
          <tr>
            <td>Parent cancel mid-batch</td>
            <td>Active signalled; queued never start; cancelled rows</td>
          </tr>
          <tr>
            <td>Expert widens tools beyond archetype</td>
            <td>Definition/build rejects (narrow-only)</td>
          </tr>
          <tr>
            <td>Claim already taken</td>
            <td>Fail closed</td>
          </tr>
          <tr>
            <td>Fresh member omits <code>after_seq</code></td>
            <td>Reads role history from start of <strong>current</strong> lead run</td>
          </tr>
          <tr>
            <td>Corrupt mailbox log</td>
            <td>Fail closed</td>
          </tr>
          <tr>
            <td>Treat swarm as durable TaskRun</td>
            <td><strong>Teaching error</strong> — different identity</td>
          </tr>
        </tbody>
      </table>
    </div>
    <aside class="history-aside">
      <p class="history-aside__tag">History contrast · competitor Expert-Team RE</p>
      <p>
        Archive <code>expert-team-implementation.md</code> reverse-engineers WorkBuddy / QoderWork: shared
        shape is “Electron shell + Claude-Code-derived CLI engine + marketplace persona md.” Maka Current
        differs on purpose — Expert Team is an in-Runtime lead persona + archetype
        <strong>narrow-only</strong> tools + team mailbox + Task Ledger claim, not another sidecar CLI /
        cloud digital-colleague stack. Cite the archive for contrast; Destination authority stays this
        section’s protocol.
      </p>
    </aside>
    <aside class="history-aside">
      <p class="history-aside__tag">Verification</p>
      <p>
        <code>bounded-swarm.test.ts</code> · <code>agent-swarm-tools.test.ts</code> ·
        <code>expert-team.test.ts</code>. Outline:
        <code>docs/research/agent-swarm-expert-team-deep-outline.md</code>.
      </p>
    </aside>
  </Section>

  <Section
    id="crash"
    label="§04 · Recovery"
    title="Crash, corrupt tail, and current recovery power"
    lede="Rebuildable control facts ≠ automatic execution resume."
  >
    <p>File TaskRunStore read rules:</p>
    <ul class="plain-list">
      <li>Newline-terminated valid events replay in order</li>
      <li>Complete but unparsable lines → <code>event_corrupt</code>, enter projection warnings</li>
      <li>A final non-newline-terminated partial tail is ignored</li>
      <li>Events with mismatched TaskRun ID never enter a valid projection</li>
      <li>Multiple terminal events → warning; today last terminal wins</li>
    </ul>
    <p>
      Still missing as general capabilities: a scheduler that enumerates and claims non-terminal
      TaskRuns; deciding whether a <code>running</code> Attempt is live or its owner is dead;
      cross-process writer lease/fencing; restore from workspace snapshot + Runtime high water;
      idempotent new-Attempt preparation; unified resume from arbitrary parked/blocked/budget states.
    </p>
  </Section>

  <Section
    id="target"
    label="§04 · Target"
    title="A real Durable Task Loop needs paired high waters"
    lede="Task Event high water alone is not enough; a recovery point binds at least five state classes."
  >
    <DiagramFigure
      caption="Fig. 7 · Target DurableTaskCheckpoint: Task / Runtime / Workspace / Budget / Owner high waters must bind before safe takeover."
      alt="Five high-water columns feed a checkpoint, then rebuild projection and choose nextAction."
    >
      <DurableCheckpointFlow />
    </DiagramFigure>
    <pre class="code-block" aria-label="DurableTaskCheckpoint shape">DurableTaskCheckpoint
  task:      taskRunId, taskEventHighWater, policyVersion
  runtime:   sessionId, completedRunIds, runtimeEventHighWaterByRun
  workspace: snapshotId, manifestHash, carrierIdentity
  budget:    attemptsUsed, runtimeStepsUsed, elapsedAccounting
  control:   nextAction, parkedInboxItemId?, ownerLease / fencingToken</pre>
    <p>
      This is a set of recovery invariants, not a field promise: Task and Runtime high waters must
      agree; workspace snapshot must pair with the same boundary; budget must restore rather than
      re-time (distinguish active / parked / scheduler downtime); owner fencing must block double
      Attempts and double-written terminals. Target still uses an idempotent new Attempt as the primary
      recovery unit — it does not try to revive provider sockets or live tool processes.
    </p>
    <div class="stub">
      <p class="stub__tag">Current vs Target</p>
      <p>
        Current: Task identity, append-only Task Events, Attempt lifecycle, three budget layers,
        Heavy-task progress/evidence, permission Inbox, and distinct Harbor / Autonomous / parked
        continuation paths. Target: versioned checkpoint, scheduler claim, durable budget, workspace
        snapshot + fencing, unified parked-state protocol — not to be taught as already guaranteed.
      </p>
    </div>
  </Section>

  <Section
    id="failure"
    label="§04 · Failure"
    title="Stop on an explainable boundary — do not pretend you can still continue"
    lede="Fail closed on budgets and ownership; do not invent a live world from a ledger alone."
  >
    <ul class="plain-list">
      <li>Budget / hard cap hit → stop the unattended loop; never bypass <code>enforceCaps()</code> with “one more try.”</li>
      <li>Permission fail-closed or park → no side effects without a grant; parked resume must write grant facts.</li>
      <li>Late grant → refuse to rewrite the permission facts of an old tool call (no post-hoc authorization).</li>
      <li>After restart, missing workspace / executor ownership evidence → restore control-plane projection only; do not claim live takeover.</li>
      <li>Prior Attempt RuntimeEvents may optionally replay into context — never pretend the tool process is still running.</li>
      <li>Corrupt / mismatched / multi-terminal → warnings must stay observable; conflicts must not vanish silently.</li>
    </ul>
  </Section>

  <Section
    id="not"
    label="§04 · Not"
    title="What the Durable Task Loop is not"
    lede="Draw the boundary so a long task is not sold as an immortal Invocation or a Memory system."
  >
    <ul class="plain-list">
      <li><strong>Not an unbounded Turn</strong> — progress moves through multiple bounded Attempts.</li>
      <li><strong>Not stuffing full history back into the model</strong> — cross-Attempt state comes from bounded progress/evidence projection.</li>
      <li><strong>Not a Memory system</strong> — serves one concrete long goal, not a cross-task preference store.</li>
      <li><strong>Not the workspace itself</strong> — the Task Event Log may cite a lease/snapshot; it does not replace file bytes.</li>
      <li><strong>Not hot recovery of the same Invocation</strong> — the recommended recovery unit is a new Turn/Attempt.</li>
      <li><strong>Not the Session task ledger</strong> — short-key todos are advisory; see <a href="#ledger">#ledger</a>.</li>
    </ul>
    <p class="figure-note">
      Invariants to protect: stable <code>taskRunId</code>; bounded attempts; append before project;
      explicit continuation; budget caps dominate policy; no post-hoc authorization; progress bounded
      and source-bearing; workspace claims explicit; Runtime facts remain separate; conflicts
      observable.
    </p>
  </Section>

